    bool IsComplete() const { return isComplete; }

You could certainly make isComplete a public member and access it with textBox.isComplete. However, the primary reason for having a function like IsComplete() is to adhere to good object-oriented design principles, specifically encapsulation. Hereâ€™s why:

â€¢ Encapsulation (keeping data private): If the class fields (like isComplete) stay private, you maintain control over how they are accessed or modified. Later on, if you decide to add extra logic whenever you check isCompleteâ€”like logging usage, triggering events, or performing additional checksâ€”you can do so directly inside the IsComplete() function without changing any external code.

â€¢ Ensuring read-only access when desired: Providing a const function that returns a private member is a simple way to allow read-only access. If isComplete were public, nothing would stop other parts of the code from mistakenly modifying it.

â€¢ Future flexibility: If you want to rename or remove isComplete altogether later on, you can keep the IsComplete() function return type or logic consistent (thus not breaking your entire codebase).

So, while itâ€™s not wrong to make isComplete public and access it directly, having an accessor function is a common practice that keeps your class flexible and well-encapsulated.
